From: Kenneth Kasilag <kenneth@kasilag.me>
Date: Fri, 03 Jul 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] net: ethernet: qualcomm: ppe: document the hardware offload series

Add a design document for the offload series that follows: the
architecture of the L2 switchdev bridge offload, VLAN-aware bridging,
multicast and the netfilter flowtable offload, the datapath invariants
the implementation relies on, the sources the hardware programming was
derived from, and what remains unimplemented or unverified on
hardware.

Signed-off-by: Kenneth Kasilag <kenneth@kasilag.me>
---
--- /dev/null
+++ b/drivers/net/ethernet/qualcomm/ppe/README.offload
@@ -0,0 +1,283 @@
+Qualcomm PPE hardware offload
+=============================
+
+The PPE (packet processing engine) is the switch-and-offload block of
+the Qualcomm IPQ network SoCs. This series adds hardware bridging,
+routing and NAT to its mainline driver through the standard Linux
+offload interfaces - switchdev for L2 bridging, netfilter flowtables
+for L3 flows - with no vendor frameworks and no new UAPI. Everything a
+patch offloads keeps working through the ordinary software path when
+the hardware cannot express it.
+
+The PPE register layer is shared across two silicon generations, HPPE
+(IPQ807x) and APPE (IPQ9574): the vendor SSDK drives both with one set
+of L2, L3 and flow accessors. The offload is therefore written against
+a per-SoC variant rather than a single chip. IPQ9574 is the generation
+it is wired up and described for here; an HPPE part reuses the same
+table and flow programming and supplies only its own EDMA glue, as the
+variant section spells out.
+
+Starting point
+--------------
+
+Mainline ships the PPE core as infrastructure only: clocks and resets,
+buffer and queue management, the scheduler, service codes and the port
+MACs. L2 forwarding is deliberately parked - every port punts to the
+CPU through the invalid-VSI redirect, all 64 VSIs (virtual switch
+instances, the hardware bridge domains) flood to the CPU port only,
+and ppe_bridge_init() notes that forwarding begins "only after
+switchdev is supported later". The preceding EDMA patches of this
+target add the per-port net devices and DMA, which makes the PPE a
+multi-port NIC with all forwarding in software. This series is the
+switchdev consumer the mainline driver anticipates.
+
+The offload is plain switchdev, not DSA: the EDMA is per-port DMA into
+the SoC, there is no conduit interface and no tagging protocol, so the
+DSA model does not fit (compare the realtek target, which bridges
+switch ports the same way).
+
+Supported hardware and the SoC variant
+--------------------------------------
+
+struct ppe_variant, attached to the compatible as match data and read
+at probe, holds the parameters that differ between the generations:
+the PPPoE session table depth (64 entries on APPE, 16 on HPPE), the
+port shaper token clock (353 against 300 MHz), and whether the on-die
+tunnel engine and the virtual ports (PPE port numbers 64..255 that
+bind non-PPE net devices) are present - both APPE only. The shared
+table geometry (flow, host, VSI, translation, router MAC, public IP
+and next hop) is identical between the generations and stays in the
+compile-time PPE_*_ENTRIES macros; only what actually diverges lives
+in the variant.
+
+                                  APPE (IPQ9574)     HPPE (IPQ807x)
+  switchdev bridge, VLAN, MDB     yes                register-portable
+  FDB with software ageing        yes                register-portable
+  L3 flows (IPv4 NAT, IPv6)       yes                register-portable
+  PPPoE offload                   yes, 64 sessions   portable, 16
+  VLAN uplinks                    yes                register-portable
+  single-copy flood               yes                needs EDMA support
+  TBF port shaper                 yes                register-portable
+  on-die tunnel engine seam       present            absent
+  virtual ports (wireless)        present            absent
+
+"Register-portable" means the table and flow programming applies
+unchanged; what an HPPE port supplies is the EDMA glue, not new PPE
+code. Bringing one up needs an EDMA driver for that generation's
+descriptors (the IPQ807x EDMA/UNIPHY rework in the qualcommax target
+grows one) meeting the CPU-port contract below, and a variant instance
+with the PPPoE table relocated to its HPPE address. The virtual-port
+work does not carry over - HPPE offloads wireless through its NSS
+firmware cores, which OpenWrt leaves idle - so wireless there stays on
+the CPU.
+
+L2 bridge offload
+-----------------
+
+A VLAN-unaware software bridge is backed by one VSI; joining binds the
+port to the VSI and enables its bridge TX MAC, leaving reverts to the
+parked state, so failure at any point falls back to a software bridge.
+The CPU port is a member of every VSI: packets without an FDB hit
+flood to the CPU and reach the software ports of the bridge (wireless
+interfaces). Received packets carry skb->offload_fwd_mark and all
+ports share one parent switch ID, so the bridge does not repeat
+forwarding the hardware already did. In the other direction,
+VLAN-unaware bridges hand over a single copy of flooded packets (TX
+forwarding offload), which the EDMA replicates through a bitmap
+destination in the transmit descriptor; the bitmaps mirror the flood
+flags, the offloaded groups and the spanning tree states, since an
+explicit destination bypasses those checks in hardware.
+
+ - FDB, downwards: user-added and bridge-local entries are written
+   through the FDB operation registers as static entries. Entries the
+   bridge learns on foreign ports (wireless) are installed towards the
+   CPU port - assisted learning - since CPU-port learning is off and
+   known unicast to such stations would otherwise flood the VSI
+   forever.
+
+ - FDB, upwards: a poller walks the 2048-entry hardware FDB, reports
+   newly learned entries to the bridge and ages them. The hardware
+   refreshes the two-bit hit_age of an entry on a source address hit;
+   the poller knocks active entries down one step and deletes entries
+   that stay knocked down past the bridge ageing time. The hardware's
+   own aging timer is zero out of reset and stays unused (References).
+
+ - Spanning tree: bridge port states map to the per-port CST state;
+   BPDUs are trapped to the CPU through an RFDB/APP_CTRL rule with
+   ingress STP bypass, otherwise a blocking port would never receive
+   them and no loop could ever break.
+
+ - Bridge port flags: BR_LEARNING gates hardware learning,
+   BR_FLOOD/BR_MCAST_FLOOD/BR_BCAST_FLOOD gate membership in the
+   per-VSI flood bitmaps.
+
+VLAN-aware bridging backs each VLAN of a bridge with its own VSI.
+Ingress VLAN translation rules, matching by port bitmap so they scale
+with VLANs rather than ports times VLANs, assign tagged and
+PVID-untagged packets to the VSI; per-VSI egress tag modes provide
+tagged or untagged egress per port; translation misses drop, which is
+the ingress side of VLAN filtering. Resource exhaustion (64 VSIs, 128
+rules) fails only the VLAN object at hand.
+
+Multicast without snooping floods to the members with BR_MCAST_FLOOD,
+exactly as the software bridge treats groups outside its MDB. With
+snooping, the MDB is offloaded as FDB entries with port-bitmap
+destinations. Every group entry includes the CPU port, so membership
+reports keep reaching the snooping bridge, software ports receive the
+group through it, and host joins need no extra handling.
+
+L3 flow offload
+---------------
+
+PPE port net devices accept flow block bindings through
+ndo_setup_tc(TC_SETUP_FT), the same glue mtk_eth_soc uses, so
+nf_flowtable rules land in the hardware flow table. Packets addressed
+to a MAC in the router MAC table take the route path; a flow hit
+forwards through a next hop entry carrying the egress port, the MAC
+rewrites, the egress VLAN and the NAT addresses. The router MAC and
+egress L3 interface tables are maintained from the source-MAC rewrite
+of the rules: the egress source MAC of one direction is the MAC the
+reverse direction ingresses on. IPv4 flows support one NAT direction
+each - SNAT source addresses come from the 16-entry public IP table -
+which matches netfilter offloading each direction as its own rule;
+IPv6 flows are routed, never translated. A root TBF qdisc on a port
+offloads to its egress token bucket shaper, replacing the CPU cost of
+software shaping.
+
+Two WAN encapsulations ride on the same flow path. A flow leaving
+through a PPPoE WAN encapsulates in hardware: the push action of the
+rule maps to a session-owned L3 interface carrying the session ID, and
+the PPPoE session table terminates the reverse direction, whose rule
+arrives as a plain flow of the inner tuple. VLAN uplinks (a tagged
+WAN, or a routed VLAN over a port) work the same way on ingress: the
+VLAN match key of the decap direction maps to a slot owning an ingress
+translation rule, a reserved VSI and an L3 interface bound through the
+L3_VSI table, while the egress push comes from the next hop entry.
+
+A flow whose egress device is not a PPE port - a wireless VAP -
+offloads through a virtual port: a PPE port number bound to the
+device, forwarded to like any egress port but backed by the CPU, so
+the packet lands on an EDMA ring already NAT'd and rewritten and the
+receive path transmits it out the device. Only this wired-to-wireless
+direction is hardware assisted; the reverse stays on the software fast
+path, which fits a download-heavy wireless client. The binding carries
+no bridging - a wireless port bridged in hardware is not the target,
+only routed and NAT'd egress to the device - and the egress source MAC
+rewrite sits on an L3 interface the virtual port reserves past the
+PPPoE and VLAN-uplink ones. Virtual ports are an APPE feature.
+
+Flow misses and rejected rules take the ordinary software path, and
+per-flow hit counters feed the flowtable statistics. Flows egressing a
+link-down port stop reporting activity so the flowtable expires and
+re-offloads them: hardware-forwarded packets never revalidate the
+route in software, and the hit counters count at ingress lookup
+whether or not egress delivery works. A route or neighbor that changes
+on the far side of a link that stays up is the remaining blind spot -
+such a flow keeps forwarding to the stale destination until its
+conntrack entry dies (the hardware flow aging engine, deliberately
+unused, could serve as a periodic revalidation net; see below).
+
+Datapath invariants worth knowing:
+
+ - CPU-transmitted packets bypass the MY_MAC check, flow lookup and
+   flow action (the EDMA service code masks them at init), so
+   software-forwarded traffic cannot be NATed twice.
+
+ - Host table entries keep the LAN/WAN bit clear, so every flow
+   classifies as LAN-to-LAN and the flow key stays the source IP,
+   matching the layout the driver writes (inline source IP, host
+   destination IP). Never set the LAN/WAN bits without revisiting
+   FLOW_CTRL1 key selection.
+
+ - The host entry of a destination is keyed by that address alone, so
+   every flow routed to it shares one entry. The driver refcounts them
+   by destination and removes a host entry only with the last of its
+   flows; the combined flow-and-host delete would otherwise strip a
+   host still in use by a sibling flow.
+
+ - The hardware FDB flush command is global and includes static
+   entries; all selective flushes are software walks.
+
+CPU-port driver contract
+------------------------
+
+The offload leans on the CPU-port net device driver (the EDMA here)
+for a few things. This is the seam another generation's driver
+implements, and the whole of what an HPPE EDMA driver has to provide:
+
+ - dispatch ndo_setup_tc(TC_SETUP_FT) to the flowtable offload and
+   TC_SETUP_QDISC_TBF to the port shaper;
+ - report the carrier of each PPE port to
+   ppe_flowtable_port_carrier(), which gates the stale-flow expiry;
+ - transmit one copy of a flooded packet through the port-bitmap
+   destination of the transmit descriptor, driven by the per-VSI flood
+   bitmaps;
+ - for the virtual-port work, deliver a receive descriptor whose
+   destination is a virtual port to its bound net device, and map a
+   transmit queue to the port.
+
+References
+----------
+
+Register and table layouts, operation protocols and reset defaults
+come from the public SSDK source (qca-ssdk NHSS.QSDK.14.0, the
+adpt_hppe_* and hppe_*_reg.h files), which is accurate for the L2,
+VLAN and L3 blocks of this SoC. The driver's own register writes were
+cross-checked against it, including the MAC byte order of the router
+MAC, next hop and egress L3 interface tables (the SSDK's mac_0/mac_1
+and mac_da_0/mac_da_1 packings) and the base index of a double-width
+IPv6 flow's hit counter.
+
+Where behavior could not be derived from source, the stock QWRT
+firmware's binaries were disassembled (Ghidra). The vendor driver
+never programs the FDB AGE_TIMER - its ageing-time setter has no
+callers - and instead deletes hardware entries when the software
+bridge ages them, which is why this series ages from the poller; its
+control-packet init programs the same BPDU trap rule used here; and
+the per-VSI egress tag field is two bits per port of
+tag/untag/unmodified modes, not a bitmap. The same disassembly settled
+the virtual-port programming: a wireless virtual port forwards on an
+invalid VSI (it is routed, not bridged), accepts any address, is
+backed by the CPU port and marked active, with learning off
+(ppe_drv_port_alloc); a packet reaches it on receive through the
+destination info of the descriptor (edma_rx_napi_poll); and the vendor
+refcounts host entries by address (ppe_drv_host_ref/deref), which is
+why this series does too.
+
+Structural models from mainline: mtk_ppe_offload.c for the flowtable
+glue, the DSA drivers for assisted learning and switchdev conventions.
+
+Remaining work
+--------------
+
+Not yet implemented, in rough order of usefulness:
+
+ - Wireless direct switching (the vendor's PPE-DS): the downlink to a
+   wireless client is offloaded through a virtual port, but it still
+   crosses the CPU once. Direct switching hands the flow between the
+   PPE and the Wi-Fi hardware with no CPU touch, which needs Wi-Fi
+   driver ring support the mainline ath12k does not have. Offloading
+   the wireless-to-wired uplink (injecting a virtual port's transmit
+   back into the PPE) is a nearer step left for later.
+ - Tunnels: the SoC has an on-die tunnel engine (the tunnel lookup
+   block, whose PPPoE session table this series already uses, plus the
+   tunnel fields of the egress L3 interfaces) able to terminate and
+   generate VXLAN, GENEVE and MAP-T style encapsulations without any
+   external accelerator. The flowtable offload dispatches rules with
+   tunnel (ENC_*) keys to a stub, gated on the variant tunnel-engine
+   flag, which is where an implementation would slot in. IPsec is a
+   different story: it needs the EIP-197 crypto engine, a separate
+   device with its own firmware, and is out of scope.
+ - QoS beyond the root TBF offload and the mainline scheduler defaults
+   (the hardware also has per-queue and flow shapers and a full
+   scheduler hierarchy), and NAT66.
+ - MSTP cannot be offloaded at all: the CST state is per port, not per
+   VSI, so only a single spanning tree maps to hardware.
+
+Hardware behaviors assumed from documentation and vendor code but
+still to be confirmed on a board: that a source-address hit refreshes
+hit_age while the aging engine is off (otherwise idle-looking active
+stations are aged and immediately re-learned, a transient flood); that
+the unmodified egress tag mode preserves tags end to end on
+VLAN-unaware bridges; and whether a long hardware flow aging timer is
+usable as a revalidation net for the stale-route blind spot above.
